#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:116
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ ls -1R tftpboot/\n"
" tftpboot/:\n"
" initrd0.img\n"
" pxelinux.0\n"
" pxelinux.cfg/\n"
" vmlinuz0\n"
" \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" tftpboot/pxelinux.cfg:\n"
" default\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:126
msgid "32 OR 64 BIT VIRT-P2V?"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:128
msgid ""
"Virt-p2v can convert any 32 or 64 bit guest, regardless of whether virt-p2v "
"itself is built as a 32 or 64 bit binary.  The only restriction is that 64 "
"bit virt-p2v cannot run on 32 bit hardware."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:132
msgid ""
"Old virt-p2v 0.9 was always built as a 32 bit (i686) ISO.  This meant that "
"the CD could be booted on any 32- or 64-bit i686 or x86-64 hardware, and "
"could convert any guest.  The old virt-p2v ISO shipped by Red Hat was based "
"on Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) 6."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:137
msgid ""
"Since RHEL 7 dropped support for 32 bit machines, current virt-p2v on RHEL "
"can only be built for 64 bit.  It cannot run on old 32 bit only hardware."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:141
msgid ""
"Fedora virt-p2v ISOs are generally built for 32 bit, so like the old RHEL 6-"
"based virt-p2v 0.9 they can boot on any hardware."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:144
msgid "TESTING VIRT-P2V USING QEMU"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:146
msgid "TESTING THE P2V ISO USING QEMU"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:148
msgid "You can use qemu to test-boot the P2V ISO:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:150
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" qemu-kvm -m 1024 -hda /tmp/guest.img -cdrom /tmp/livecd-p2v.iso -boot d\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:152
msgid ""
"Note that C<-hda> is the (virtual) system that you want to convert (for test "
"purposes).  It could be any guest type supported by L<virt-v2v(1)>, "
"including Windows or Red Hat Enterprise Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:156
msgid "TESTING PXE SUPPORT USING QEMU"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:162
msgid ""
"Unpack the tftpboot directory into F</tmp> (so it appears as F</tmp/"
"tftpboot>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:167
msgid ""
"Copy F<pxelinux.0> and F<ldlinux.c32> from syslinux (usually from F</usr/"
"share/syslinux>) into F</tmp/tftpboot>."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:172
msgid ""
"Adjust the C<APPEND> line in F</tmp/tftpboot/pxelinux.cfg/default> if "
"required.  See L<virt-p2v(1)/KERNEL COMMAND LINE CONFIGURATION>."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:177
msgid ""
"Run qemu like this so that it acts as a TFTP and BOOTP server, emulating a "
"netboot:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:180
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" qemu-kvm \\\n"
"     -m 4096 -hda /tmp/guest.img \\\n"
"     -boot n \\\n"
"     -netdev user,id=unet,tftp=/tmp/tftpboot,bootfile=/pxelinux.0 \\\n"
"     -device virtio-net-pci,netdev=unet \\\n"
"     -serial stdio\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:187
msgid ""
"Note that this requires considerably more memory because the PXE image is "
"loaded into memory.  Also that qemu's TFTP server is very slow and the virt-"
"p2v PXE image is very large, so it can appear to \"hang\" after pxelinux "
"starts up."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:196
msgid ""
"You can inject an SSH identity (private key) file to the kickstart and hence "
"into the ISO using the I<--inject-ssh-identity> option.  Note that you "
"I<cannot> inject a key once the ISO has been built."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:209
msgid ""
"The private key should be added to the kickstart file and then discarded:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:212
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" virt-p2v-make-kickstart [...] --inject-ssh-identity id_rsa\n"
" rm id_rsa\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:215
msgid ""
"The ISO can then be built from the kickstart in the usual way (see above), "
"and it will contain the embedded SSH identity (F</var/tmp/id_rsa>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:243
msgid ""
"Add an SSH identity (private key) file into the kickstart.  See L</ADDING AN "
"SSH IDENTITY> above."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../p2v/virt-p2v-make-kickstart.pod:250
msgid ""
"Write kickstart to C<OUTPUT>.  If not specified, the default is F<p2v.ks> in "
"the current directory."
msgstr ""

