#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:768
msgid "RHEL 4"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:770
msgid "SELinux relabel appears to hang forever"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:772
msgid ""
"In RHEL E<le> 4.7 there was a bug which causes SELinux relabelling to appear "
"to hang forever at:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:775
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" *** Warning -- SELinux relabel is required. ***\n"
" *** Disabling security enforcement.         ***\n"
" *** Relabeling could take a very long time, ***\n"
" *** depending on file system size.          ***\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:780
msgid ""
"In reality it is waiting for you to press a key (but there is no visual "
"indication of this).  You can either hit the C<[Return]> key, at which point "
"the guest will finish relabelling and reboot, or you can install "
"policycoreutils E<ge> 1.18.1-4.13 before starting the v2v conversion.  See "
"also L<https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=244636>"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:787
msgid "WINDOWS"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:789
msgid "Boot failure: 0x0000007B"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:791
msgid ""
"This boot failure is caused by Windows being unable to find or load the "
"right disk driver (eg. F<viostor.sys>).  If you experience this error, here "
"are some things to check:"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:799
msgid ""
"First ensure that the guest boots on the source hypervisor before conversion."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:804
msgid ""
"Check you have the Windows virtio drivers available in F</usr/share/virtio-"
"win>, and that virt-v2v did not print any warning about not being able to "
"install virtio drivers."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:808
msgid ""
"On S<Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7>, you will need to install the signed "
"drivers available in the C<virtio-win> package.  If you do not have access "
"to the signed drivers, then you will probably need to disable driver signing "
"in the boot menus."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:815
msgid ""
"Check that you are presenting a virtio-blk interface (B<not> virtio-scsi and "
"B<not> ide) to the guest.  On the qemu/KVM command line you should see "
"something similar to this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:819
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" ... -drive file=windows-sda,if=virtio ...\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:821
msgid "In libvirt XML, you should see:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:823
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" <target dev='vda' bus='virtio'/>\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:827
msgid ""
"Check that Windows Group Policy does not prevent the driver from being "
"installed or used.  Try deleting Windows Group Policy before conversion."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:833
msgid ""
"Check there is no anti-virus or other software which implements Group Policy-"
"like prohibitions on installing or using new drivers."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:838
msgid ""
"Enable boot debugging and check the F<viostor.sys> driver is being loaded."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:843
msgid "OpenStack and Windows reactivation"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:845
msgid ""
"OpenStack does not offer stable device / PCI addresses to guests.  Every "
"time it creates or starts a guest, it regenerates the libvirt XML for that "
"guest from scratch.  The libvirt XML will have no E<lt>addressE<gt> fields.  "
"Libvirt will then assign addresses to devices, in a predictable manner.  "
"Addresses may change if any of the following are true:"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:856
msgid "A new disk or network device has been added or removed from the guest."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:860
msgid "The version of OpenStack or (possibly) libvirt has changed."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:864
msgid ""
"Because Windows does not like \"hardware\" changes of this kind, it may "
"trigger Windows reactivation."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:867
msgid ""
"This can also prevent booting with a 7B error [see previous section] if the "
"guest has group policy containing C<Device Installation Restrictions>."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:871
msgid "UEFI"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:873
msgid ""
"VMware allows you to present UEFI firmware to guests (instead of the "
"ordinary PC BIOS).  Virt-v2v can convert these guests, but requires that "
"UEFI is supported by the target hypervisor."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:877
msgid ""
"Currently KVM supports OVMF, a partially open source UEFI firmware, and can "
"run these guests."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:880
msgid ""
"Since OVMF support was only recently added to KVM (in 2014/2015), not all "
"target environments support UEFI guests yet:"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:885
msgid "UEFI on libvirt, qemu"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:887
msgid ""
"Supported.  Virt-v2v will generate the correct libvirt XML (metadata)  "
"automatically, but note that the same version of OVMF must be installed on "
"the conversion host as is installed on the target hypervisor, else you will "
"have to adjust paths in the metadata."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:892
msgid "UEFI on OpenStack"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:894 ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:898
msgid "Not supported."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:896
msgid "UEFI on RHEV"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:902
msgid "NETWORKS AND BRIDGES"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:904
msgid ""
"Guests are usually connected to one or more networks, and when converted to "
"the target hypervisor you usually want to reconnect those networks at the "
"destination.  The options I<--network> and I<--bridge> allow you to do that."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:909
msgid ""
"If you are unsure of what networks and bridges are in use on the source "
"hypervisor, then you can examine the source metadata (libvirt XML, vCenter "
"information, etc.).  Or you can run virt-v2v with the I<--print-source> "
"option which causes virt-v2v to print out the information it has about the "
"guest on the source and then exit."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:915
msgid ""
"In the I<--print-source> output you will see a section showing the guest's "
"Network Interface Cards (NICs):"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:918
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v [-i ...] --print-source name\n"
" [...]\n"
" NICs:\n"
"     Network \"default\" mac: 52:54:00:d0:cf:0e\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:923
msgid ""
"This is typical of a libvirt guest: It has a single network interface "
"connected to a network called C<default>."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:926
msgid ""
"To map a specific network to a target network, for example C<default> on the "
"source to C<rhevm> on the target, use:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:929
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" virt-v2v [...] --network default:rhevm\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:931
msgid "To map every network to a target network, use:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:933
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" virt-v2v [...] --network rhevm\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:935
msgid ""
"Bridges are handled in the same way, but you have to use the I<--bridge> "
"option instead.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:938
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v [-i ...] --print-source name\n"
" [...]\n"
" NICs:\n"
"     Bridge \"br0\"\n"
" \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:943
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v [...] --bridge br0:targetbr\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:945
msgid "INPUT FROM VMWARE VCENTER SERVER"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:947
msgid "Virt-v2v is able to import guests from VMware vCenter Server."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:949
msgid ""
"vCenter E<ge> 5.0 is required.  Virt-v2v B<cannot> import guests directly "
"from an ESXi hypervisor.  If you don't have vCenter, using OVA is "
"recommended instead (see L</INPUT FROM VMWARE OVA> below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:953
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v uses libvirt for access to vCenter, and therefore the input mode "
"should be I<-i libvirt>.  As this is the default, you don't need to specify "
"it on the command line."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:957
msgid "VCENTER: REMOVE VMWARE TOOLS FROM WINDOWS GUESTS"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:959 ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1130
msgid ""
"For Windows guests, you should remove VMware tools before conversion.  "
"Although this is not strictly necessary, and the guest will still be able to "
"run, if you don't do this then the converted guest will complain on every "
"boot.  The tools cannot be removed after conversion because the uninstaller "
"checks if it is running on VMware and refuses to start (which is also the "
"reason that virt-v2v cannot remove them)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:966 ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1137
msgid ""
"This is not necessary for Linux guests, as virt-v2v is able to remove VMware "
"tools."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:969
msgid "VCENTER: URI"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:971
msgid "The libvirt URI of a vCenter server looks something like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:973
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" vpx://user@server/Datacenter/esxi\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:975
msgid "where:"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:979
msgid "C<user@>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:981
msgid "is the (optional, but recommended) user to connect as."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:983
msgid ""
"If the username contains a backslash (eg. C<DOMAIN\\USER>) then you will "
"need to URI-escape that character using C<%5c>: C<DOMAIN%5cUSER> (5c is the "
"hexadecimal ASCII code for backslash.)  Other punctuation may also have to "
"be escaped."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:990
msgid "is the vCenter Server (I<not> hypervisor)."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:992
msgid "C<Datacenter>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:994
msgid "is the name of the datacenter."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:996
msgid ""
"If the name contains a space, replace it with the URI-escape code C<%20>."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:999
msgid "C<esxi>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1001
msgid "is the name of the ESXi hypervisor running the guest."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1005
msgid ""
"If the VMware deployment is using folders, then these may need to be added "
"to the URI, eg:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1008
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" vpx://user@server/Folder/Datacenter/esxi\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1010
msgid ""
"For full details of libvirt URIs, see: L<http://libvirt.org/drvesx.html>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1012
msgid "Typical errors from libvirt / virsh when the URI is wrong include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1018
msgid "Could not find datacenter specified in [...]"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1022
msgid "Could not find compute resource specified in [...]"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1026
msgid "Path [...] does not specify a compute resource"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1030
msgid "Path [...] does not specify a host system"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1034
msgid "Could not find host system specified in [...]"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1038
msgid "VCENTER: TEST LIBVIRT CONNECTION TO VCENTER"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1040
msgid ""
"Use the L<virsh(1)> command to list the guests on the vCenter Server like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1043
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virsh -c 'vpx://root@vcenter.example.com/Datacenter/esxi' list --all\n"
" Enter root's password for vcenter.example.com: ***\n"
" \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1046
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Id    Name                           State\n"
" ----------------------------------------------------\n"
"  -     Fedora 20                      shut off\n"
"  -     Windows 2003                   shut off\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1051
msgid ""
"If you get an error \"Peer certificate cannot be authenticated with given CA "
"certificates\" or similar, then you can either import the vCenter host's "
"certificate, or bypass signature verification by adding the C<?no_verify=1> "
"flag:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1056
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virsh -c 'vpx://root@vcenter.example.com/Datacenter/esxi?no_verify=1' list --all\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1058 ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1229
msgid ""
"You should also try dumping the metadata from any guest on your server, like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1061
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virsh -c 'vpx://root@vcenter.example.com/Datacenter/esxi' dumpxml \"Windows 2003\"\n"
" <domain type='vmware'>\n"
"   <name>Windows 2003</name>\n"
"   [...]\n"
" </domain>\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1067
msgid ""
"B<If the above commands do not work, then virt-v2v is not going to work "
"either>.  Fix your libvirt configuration and/or your VMware vCenter Server "
"before continuing."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1071
msgid "VCENTER: IMPORTING A GUEST"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1073
msgid "To import a particular guest from vCenter Server, do:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1075
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v -ic 'vpx://root@vcenter.example.com/Datacenter/esxi?no_verify=1' \\\n"
"   \"Windows 2003\" \\\n"
"   -o local -os /var/tmp\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1079
msgid ""
"where C<Windows 2003> is the name of the guest (which must be shut down)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1082
msgid ""
"Note that you may be asked for the vCenter password I<twice>.  This happens "
"once because libvirt needs it, and a second time because virt-v2v itself "
"connects directly to the server.  Use I<--password-file> to supply a "
"password via a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1087 ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1257
msgid ""
"In this case the output flags are set to write the converted guest to a "
"temporary directory as this is just an example, but you can also write to "
"libvirt or any other supported target."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1091
msgid "VCENTER: NON-ADMINISTRATOR ROLE"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1093
msgid ""
"Instead of using the vCenter Administrator role, you can create a custom non-"
"administrator role to perform the conversion.  You will however need to give "
"it a minimum set of permissions as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1101
msgid "Create a custom role in vCenter."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1105
msgid "Enable (check) the following objects:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1107
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" Datastore:\n"
"  - Browse datastore\n"
"  - Low level file operations\n"
" \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" Session:\n"
"  - Validate session\n"
" \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1114
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" Virtual Machine:\n"
"   Provisioning:\n"
"     - Allow disk access\n"
"     - Allow read-only disk access\n"
"     - Guest Operating system management by VIX API\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1122
msgid "INPUT FROM VMWARE OVA"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1124
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v is able to import guests from VMware's OVA (Open Virtualization "
"Appliance) files.  Only OVAs exported from VMware vSphere will work."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1128
msgid "OVA: REMOVE VMWARE TOOLS FROM WINDOWS GUESTS"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1140
msgid "OVA: CREATE OVA"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1142
msgid ""
"To create an OVA in vSphere, use the \"Export OVF Template\" option (from "
"the VM context menu, or from the File menu).  Either \"Folder of files"
"\" (OVF) or \"Single file\" (OVA) will work, but OVA is probably easier to "
"deal with.  OVA files are really just uncompressed tar files, so you can use "
"commands like C<tar tf VM.ova> to view their contents."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head3
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1149
msgid "Create OVA with ovftool"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1151
msgid "You can also use VMware's proprietary C<ovftool>:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1153
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" ovftool --noSSLVerify \\\n"
"   vi://USER:PASSWORD@esxi.example.com/VM \\\n"
"   VM.ova\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1157
msgid "To connect to vCenter:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1159
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" ovftool  --noSSLVerify \\\n"
"   vi://USER:PASSWORD@vcenter.example.com/DATACENTER-NAME/vm/VM \\\n"
"   VM.ova\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1163
msgid ""
"For Active Directory-aware authentication, you have to express the C<@> "
"character in the form of its ascii hex-code (C<%5c>):"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1166
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" vi://DOMAIN%5cUSER:PASSWORD@...\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1168
msgid "OVA: IMPORTING A GUEST"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1170
msgid "To import an OVA file called F<VM.ova>, do;"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1172
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v -i ova VM.ova -o local -os /var/tmp\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1174
msgid ""
"If you exported the guest as a \"Folder of files\", I<or> if you unpacked "
"the OVA tarball yourself, then you can point virt-v2v at the directory "
"containing the files:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1178
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v -i ova /path/to/files -o local -os /var/tmp\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1180
msgid "INPUT FROM VMWARE ESXi HYPERVISOR"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1182
msgid "Virt-v2v cannot access an ESXi hypervisor directly."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1184
msgid ""
"However you can use the L<virt-v2v-copy-to-local(1)> tool to copy the guest "
"off the hypervisor into a local file, and then convert it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1187
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" virt-v2v-copy-to-local -ic esx://esxi.example.com vmware_guest\n"
" virt-v2v -i libvirtxml vmware_guest.xml [-o options ...]\n"
" rm vmware_guest.xml vmware_guest-disk*\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1191
msgid "See L<virt-v2v-copy-to-local(1)> for further information."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1193
msgid "INPUT FROM RHEL 5 XEN"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1195
msgid "Virt-v2v is able to import Xen guests from RHEL 5 Xen hosts."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1197
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v uses libvirt for access to the remote Xen host, and therefore the "
"input mode should be I<-i libvirt>.  As this is the default, you don't need "
"to specify it on the command line."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1201
msgid "XEN: SET UP SSH-AGENT ACCESS TO XEN HOST"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1203
msgid ""
"Currently you must enable passwordless SSH access to the remote Xen host "
"from the virt-v2v conversion server."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1206
msgid ""
"You must also use ssh-agent, and add your ssh public key to F</root/.ssh/"
"authorized_keys> (on the Xen host)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1209
msgid ""
"After doing this, you should check that passwordless access works from the "
"virt-v2v server to the Xen host.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1212
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ ssh root@xen.example.com\n"
" [ logs straight into the shell, no password is requested ]\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1215
msgid ""
"Note that password-interactive and Kerberos access are B<not> supported.  "
"You B<have> to set up ssh access using ssh-agent and authorized_keys."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1219
msgid "XEN: TEST LIBVIRT CONNECTION TO REMOTE XEN HOST"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1221
msgid "Use the L<virsh(1)> command to list the guests on the remote Xen host:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1223
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virsh -c xen+ssh://root@xen.example.com list --all\n"
"  Id    Name                           State\n"
" ----------------------------------------------------\n"
"  0     Domain-0                       running\n"
"  -     rhel49-x86_64-pv               shut off\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1232
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virsh -c xen+ssh://root@xen.example.com dumpxml rhel49-x86_64-pv\n"
" <domain type='xen'>\n"
"   <name>rhel49-x86_64-pv</name>\n"
"   [...]\n"
" </domain>\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1238
msgid ""
"B<If the above commands do not work, then virt-v2v is not going to work "
"either>.  Fix your libvirt configuration or the remote server before "
"continuing."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1242
msgid ""
"B<If the guest disks are located on a host block device>, then the "
"conversion will fail.  See L</XEN OR SSH CONVERSIONS FROM BLOCK DEVICES> "
"below for a workaround."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1246
msgid "XEN: IMPORTING A GUEST"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1248
msgid "To import a particular guest from a Xen server, do:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1250
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v -ic 'xen+ssh://root@xen.example.com' \\\n"
"   rhel49-x86_64-pv \\\n"
"   -o local -os /var/tmp\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1254
msgid ""
"where C<rhel49-x86_64-pv> is the name of the guest (which must be shut down)."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1261
msgid "XEN OR SSH CONVERSIONS FROM BLOCK DEVICES"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1263
msgid ""
"It is currently not possible to convert a Xen guest (or any guest located "
"remotely over ssh) if that guest's disks are located on host block devices."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1267
msgid ""
"To tell if a Xen guest uses host block devices, look at the guest XML.  You "
"will see:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1270
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  <disk type='block' device='disk'>\n"
"    ...\n"
"    <source dev='/dev/VG/guest'/>\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1274
msgid ""
"where C<type='block'>, C<source dev=> and C</dev/...> are all indications "
"that the disk is located on a host block device."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1277
msgid ""
"This happens because the qemu ssh block driver that we use to access remote "
"disks uses the ssh sftp protocol, and this protocol cannot correctly detect "
"the size of host block devices."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1281
msgid ""
"The workaround is to copy the guest over to the conversion server.  You will "
"need sufficient space on the conversion server to store a full copy of the "
"guest."
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1285
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" virt-v2v-copy-to-local -ic xen+ssh://root@xen.example.com guest\n"
" virt-v2v -i libvirtxml guest.xml [-o options ...]\n"
" rm guest.xml guest-disk*\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1289
msgid "OUTPUT TO LIBVIRT"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1291
msgid ""
"The I<-o libvirt> option lets you upload the converted guest to a libvirt-"
"managed host.  There are several limitations:"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1298
msgid ""
"You can only use a local libvirt connection [see below for how to workaround "
"this]."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1303
msgid ""
"The I<-os pool> option must specify a directory pool, not anything more "
"exotic such as iSCSI [but see below]."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1308
msgid "You can only upload to a KVM hypervisor."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1312
msgid ""
"B<To output to a remote libvirt instance and/or a non-directory storage "
"pool> you have to use the following workaround:"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1319
msgid ""
"Use virt-v2v in I<-o local> mode to convert the guest disks and metadata "
"into a local temporary directory:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1322
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" virt-v2v [...] -o local -os /var/tmp\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1324
msgid "This creates two (or more) files in F</var/tmp> called:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1326
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" /var/tmp/NAME.xml     # the libvirt XML (metadata)\n"
" /var/tmp/NAME-sda     # the guest's first disk\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1329
msgid "(for C<NAME> substitute the guest's name)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1333
msgid "Upload the converted disk(s) into the storage pool called C<POOL>:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1335
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" size=$(stat -c%s /var/tmp/NAME-sda)\n"
" virsh vol-create-as POOL NAME-sda $size --format raw\n"
" virsh vol-upload --pool POOL NAME-sda /var/tmp/NAME-sda\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1341
msgid ""
"Edit F</var/tmp/NAME.xml> to change F</var/tmp/NAME-sda> to the pool name.  "
"In other words, locate the following bit of XML:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1344
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" <disk type='file' device='disk'>\n"
"   <driver name='qemu' type='raw' cache='none' />\n"
"   <source file='/var/tmp/NAME-sda' />\n"
"   <target dev='hda' bus='ide' />\n"
" </disk>\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1350
msgid ""
"and change two things: The C<type='file'> attribute must be changed to "
"C<type='volume'>, and the C<E<lt>sourceE<gt>> element must be changed to "
"include C<pool> and C<volume> attributes:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1354
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" <disk type='volume' device='disk'>\n"
"   ...\n"
"   <source pool='POOL' volume='NAME-sda' />\n"
"   ...\n"
" </disk>\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1362
msgid "Define the final guest in libvirt:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1364
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" virsh define /var/tmp/NAME.xml\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1368
msgid "OUTPUT TO RHEV"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1370
msgid ""
"This section only applies to the I<-o rhev> output mode.  If you use virt-"
"v2v from the RHEV-M user interface, then behind the scenes the import is "
"managed by VDSM using the I<-o vdsm> output mode (which end users should not "
"try to use directly)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1375
msgid ""
"You have to specify I<-o rhev> and an I<-os> option that points to the RHEV-"
"M Export Storage Domain.  You can either specify the NFS server and "
"mountpoint, eg. S<C<-os rhev-storage:/rhev/export>>, or you can mount that "
"first and point to the directory where it is mounted, eg. S<C<-os /tmp/"
"mnt>>.  Be careful not to point to the Data Storage Domain by accident as "
"that will not work."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1382
msgid ""
"On successful completion virt-v2v will have written the new guest to the "
"Export Storage Domain, but it will not yet be ready to run.  It must be "
"imported into RHEV using the UI before it can be used."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1386
msgid ""
"In RHEV E<ge> 2.2 this is done from the Storage tab.  Select the export "
"domain the guest was written to.  A pane will appear underneath the storage "
"domain list displaying several tabs, one of which is \"VM Import\".  The "
"converted guest will be listed here.  Select the appropriate guest an click "
"\"Import\".  See the RHEV documentation for additional details."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1393
msgid ""
"If you export several guests, then you can import them all at the same time "
"through the UI."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1396
msgid "RESOURCE REQUIREMENTS"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1398
msgid "Network"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1400
msgid ""
"The most important resource for virt-v2v appears to be network bandwidth.  "
"Virt-v2v should be able to copy guest data at gigabit ethernet speeds or "
"greater."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1404
msgid ""
"Ensure that the network connections between servers (conversion server, NFS "
"server, vCenter, Xen) are as fast and as low latency as possible."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1408
msgid "Disk space"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1410
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v places potentially large temporary files in C<$TMPDIR> (which is F</"
"var/tmp> if you don't set it).  Using tmpfs is a bad idea."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1413
msgid ""
"For each guest disk, an overlay is stored temporarily.  This stores the "
"changes made during conversion, and is used as a cache.  The overlays are "
"not particularly large - tens or low hundreds of megabytes per disk is "
"typical.  In addition to the overlay(s), input and output methods may use "
"disk space, as outlined in the table below."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1421
msgid "I<-i ova>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1423
msgid ""
"This temporarily places a full copy of the uncompressed source disks in C<"
"$TMPDIR>."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1426
msgid "I<-o glance>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1428 ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1439
msgid "This temporarily places a full copy of the output disks in C<$TMPDIR>."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1430
msgid "I<-o local>"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1432
msgid "I<-o qemu>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1434
msgid ""
"You must ensure there is sufficient space in the output directory for the "
"converted guest."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1437
msgid "I<-o null>"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1443
msgid "VMware vCenter resources"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1445
msgid ""
"Copying from VMware vCenter is currently quite slow, but we believe this to "
"be an issue with VMware.  Ensuring the VMware ESXi hypervisor and vCenter "
"are running on fast hardware with plenty of memory should alleviate this."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1450
msgid "Compute power and RAM"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1452
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v is not especially compute or RAM intensive.  If you are running "
"many parallel conversions, then you may consider allocating one CPU core and "
"between 512 MB and 1 GB of RAM per running instance."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1456
msgid "Virt-v2v can be run in a virtual machine."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1458
msgid "POST-CONVERSION TASKS"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1460
msgid "Guest network configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1462
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v cannot currently reconfigure a guest's network configuration.  If "
"the converted guest is not connected to the same subnet as the source, its "
"network configuration may have to be updated.  See also L<virt-customize(1)>."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head2
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1467
msgid "Converting a Windows guest"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1469
msgid ""
"When converting a Windows guests, the conversion process is split into two "
"stages:"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1476
msgid "Offline conversion."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1480
msgid "First boot."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1484
msgid ""
"The guest will be bootable after the offline conversion stage, but will not "
"yet have all necessary drivers installed to work correctly.  These will be "
"installed automatically the first time the guest boots."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1488
msgid ""
"B<N.B.> Take care not to interrupt the automatic driver installation process "
"when logging in to the guest for the first time, as this may prevent the "
"guest from subsequently booting correctly."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1492
msgid "FREE SPACE FOR CONVERSION"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1494
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v checks there is sufficient free space in the guest filesystem to "
"perform the conversion.  Currently it checks:"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1499
msgid "Linux root filesystem or Windows C<C:> drive"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1501
msgid "Minimum free space: 20 MB"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1503
msgid "Linux F</boot>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1505
msgid "Minimum free space: 50 MB"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1507
msgid ""
"This is because we need to build a new initramfs for some Enterprise Linux "
"conversions."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1510
msgid "Any other mountable filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1512
msgid "Minimum free space: 10 MB"
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1516
msgid "RUNNING VIRT-V2V AS ROOT OR NON-ROOT"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1518
msgid ""
"Nothing in virt-v2v inherently needs root access, and it will run just fine "
"as a non-root user.  However, certain external features may require either "
"root or a special user:"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1524
msgid "Mounting the Export Storage Domain"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1526
msgid ""
"When using I<-o rhev -os server:/esd> virt-v2v has to have sufficient "
"privileges to NFS mount the Export Storage Domain from C<server>."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1529
msgid ""
"You can avoid needing root here by mounting it yourself before running virt-"
"v2v, and passing I<-os /mountpoint> instead, but first of all read the next "
"S<section ...>"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1533
msgid "Writing to the Export Storage Domain as 36:36"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1535
msgid ""
"RHEV-M cannot read files and directories from the Export Storage Domain "
"unless they have UID:GID 36:36.  You will see VM import problems if the UID:"
"GID is not correct."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1539
msgid ""
"When you run virt-v2v I<-o rhev> as root, virt-v2v attempts to create files "
"and directories with the correct ownership.  If you run virt-v2v as non-"
"root, it will probably still work, but you will need to manually change "
"ownership after virt-v2v has finished."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1544
msgid "Writing to libvirt"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1546
msgid ""
"When using I<-o libvirt>, you may need to run virt-v2v as root so that it "
"can write to the libvirt system instance (ie. C<qemu:///system>)  and to the "
"default location for disk images (usually F</var/lib/libvirt/images>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1551
msgid ""
"You can avoid this by setting up libvirt connection authentication, see "
"L<http://libvirt.org/auth.html>.  Alternatively, use I<-oc qemu:///session>, "
"which will write to your per-user libvirt instance."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1556
msgid "Writing to Glance"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1558
msgid ""
"This does I<not> need root (in fact it probably won't work), but may require "
"either a special user and/or for you to source a script that sets "
"authentication environment variables.  Consult the Glance documentation."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1565
msgid "DEBUGGING RHEV-M IMPORT FAILURES"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1567
msgid ""
"When you export to the RHEV-M Export Storage Domain, and then import that "
"guest through the RHEV-M UI, you may encounter an import failure.  "
"Diagnosing these failures is infuriatingly difficult as the UI generally "
"hides the true reason for the failure."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1572
msgid ""
"There are two log files of interest.  The first is stored on the RHEV-M "
"server itself, and is called F</var/log/ovirt-engine/engine.log>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1576
msgid ""
"The second file, which is the most useful, is found on the SPM host (SPM "
"stands for \"Storage Pool Manager\").  This is a RHEV node that is elected "
"to do all metadata modifications in the data center, such as image or "
"snapshot creation.  You can find out which host is the current SPM from the "
"\"Hosts\" tab \"Spm Status\" column.  Once you have located the SPM, log "
"into it and grab the file F</var/log/vdsm/vdsm.log> which will contain "
"detailed error messages from low-level commands."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1585
msgid "MINIMAL XML FOR -i libvirtxml OPTION"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1587
msgid ""
"When using the I<-i libvirtxml> option, you have to supply some libvirt "
"XML.  Writing this from scratch is hard, so the template below is helpful."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1591
msgid ""
"B<Note this should only be used for testing and/or where you know what "
"you're doing!> If you have libvirt metadata for the guest, always use that "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1595
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" <domain type='kvm'>\n"
"   <name>NAME</name>\n"
"   <memory>1048576</memory>\n"
"   <vcpu>2</vcpu>\n"
"   <os>\n"
"     <type>hvm</type>\n"
"     <boot dev='hd'/>\n"
"   </os>\n"
"   <features>\n"
"     <acpi/>\n"
"     <apic/>\n"
"     <pae/>\n"
"   </features>\n"
"   <devices>\n"
"     <disk type='file' device='disk'>\n"
"       <driver name='qemu' type='raw'/>\n"
"       <source file='/path/to/disk/image'/>\n"
"       <target dev='hda' bus='ide'/>\n"
"     </disk>\n"
"     <interface type='network'>\n"
"       <mac address='52:54:00:01:02:03'/>\n"
"       <source network='default'/>\n"
"       <model type='rtl8139'/>\n"
"     </interface>\n"
"   </devices>\n"
" </domain>\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1624
msgid ""
"The I<--machine-readable> option can be used to make the output more machine "
"friendly, which is useful when calling virt-v2v from other programs, GUIs "
"etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1630
msgid ""
"Firstly use the option on its own to query the capabilities of the virt-v2v "
"binary.  Typical output looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1633
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" $ virt-v2v --machine-readable\n"
" virt-v2v\n"
" libguestfs-rewrite\n"
" input:disk\n"
" [...]\n"
" output:local\n"
" [...]\n"
" convert:enterprise-linux\n"
" convert:windows\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1646
msgid ""
"The C<input:> and C<output:> features refer to I<-i> and I<-o> (input and "
"output mode) options supported by this binary.  The C<convert:> features "
"refer to guest types that this binary knows how to convert."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1672
msgid ""
"The calling program should treat messages sent to stderr as error messages.  "
"In addition, virt-v2v exits with a non-zero status code if there was a fatal "
"error."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1678
msgid ""
"Virt-v2v E<le> 0.9.1 did not support the I<--machine-readable> option at "
"all.  The option was added when virt-v2v was rewritten in 2014."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1685
msgid "F</usr/share/virtio-win>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1687 ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1729
msgid "(Optional)"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1689
msgid ""
"If this directory is present, then virtio drivers for Windows guests will be "
"found from this directory and installed in the guest during conversion."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1699
msgid "C<TMPDIR>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1704
msgid "See the L</Disk space> section above."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1708
msgid ""
"This can point to the directory containing data files used for Windows "
"conversion."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1720
msgid "(Required when doing conversions of Windows guests)"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1722
msgid ""
"This is the RHSrvAny Windows binary, used to install a \"firstboot\" script "
"in the guest during conversion of Windows guests."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1727
msgid "F<rhev-apt.exe>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1731
msgid ""
"The RHEV Application Provisioning Tool (RHEV APT).  If this file is present, "
"then RHEV APT will be installed in the Windows guest during conversion.  "
"This tool is a guest agent which ensures that the virtio drivers remain up "
"to date when the guest is running on Red Hat Enterprise Virtualization "
"(RHEV)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1737
msgid ""
"This file comes from Red Hat Enterprise Virtualization (RHEV), and is not "
"distributed with virt-v2v."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1742
msgid "C<VIRTIO_WIN>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1744
msgid ""
"This is where VirtIO drivers for Windows are searched for (F</usr/share/"
"virtio-win> if unset).  It can be a directory I<or> point to F<virtio-win."
"iso> (CD ROM image containing drivers)."
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1748
msgid "See L<ENABLING VIRTIO>."
msgstr ""

#. type: =head1
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1754
msgid "OTHER TOOLS"
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1758
msgid "L<virt-v2v-copy-to-local(1)>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1760
msgid ""
"There are some special cases where virt-v2v cannot directly access the "
"remote hypervisor.  In that case you have to use L<virt-v2v-copy-to-"
"local(1)> to make a local copy of the guest first, followed by running "
"C<virt-v2v -i libvirtxml> to perform the conversion."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1766
msgid "L<engine-image-uploader(8)>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1768
msgid ""
"Variously called C<engine-image-uploader>, C<ovirt-image-uploader> or "
"C<rhevm-image-uploader>, this tool allows you to copy a guest from one oVirt "
"or RHEV Export Storage Domain to another.  It only permits importing a guest "
"that was previously exported from another oVirt/RHEV instance."
msgstr ""

#. type: =item
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1774
msgid "L<import-to-ovirt.pl|http://git.annexia.org/?p=import-to-ovirt.git>"
msgstr ""

#. type: textblock
#: ../v2v/virt-v2v.pod:1776
msgid ""
"This script can be used to import guests that already run on KVM to oVirt or "
